        <p>Let's look at some examples of rational functions.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-introduction-to-rational-functions">
            <statement>
                <p>Build a table and sketch the graph of the function <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x-2}</m>. Find the function's domain and range.</p>

                <p>Since <m>x=2</m> makes the denominator <m>0</m>, the function will be undefined where <m>x=2</m>. We'll start by choosing various <m>x</m>-values and plotting the associated points.</p>
                
                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
                <table xml:id="table-rational-function-intro-initial-table">
                    <caption>Initial Values of <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x-2}</m></caption>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="left"/>
                        <col halign="left"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
                            <cell>Point</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\frac{1}{-6-2}=-0.125</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-6,-0.125)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\frac{1}{-4-2}\approx -0.167</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\left(-4,-\frac{1}{6}\right)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\frac{1}{-2-2}\approx-0.25</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-2,-0.25)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\frac{1}{0-2}=-0.5</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(0,-0.5)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\frac{1}{1-2}=-1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(1,-1)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell>undefined</cell>
                            <cell></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\frac{1}{3-2}=1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(3,1)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\frac{1}{4-2}=0.5</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(4,0.5)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>


                <figure>
                    <caption>Initial Points for <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x-2}</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[]
                                \addplot [asymptote] coordinates {(2.05,-7) (2.05,7)};
                                \addplot [soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(-6,-0.125) (-4,-0.167) (-2,-0.25) (0,-0.5) (1,-1) (3,1) (4,0.5) (6,0.25)};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                </sidebyside>

                <p>Note that extra points were chosen near <m>x=2</m> in the <xref ref="table-rational-function-intro-initial-table">Table</xref>, but it's still not clear on the graph what happens really close to <m>x=2</m>. It will be essential that we include at least one <m>x</m>-value between <m>1</m> and <m>2</m> and also between <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.</p>

                <p>Further, we'll note that dividing one number by a number that is close to zero yields a large number. For example, <m>\frac{1}{0.0005}=2000</m>. In fact, the smaller the number is that we divide by, the larger our result becomes. When we plot our additional points below and connect the curve, this means that the arrows on the graph near <m>x=2</m> will either point upward or downward.</p>

                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
                <table>
                    <caption>Values of <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x-2}</m></caption>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="left"/>
                        <col halign="left"/>
