                <figure xml:id="figure-rational-function-intro-full-graph">
                    <caption>Full Graph of <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x-2}</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[]
                                \addplot [asymptote] coordinates {(2.05,-7) (2.05,7)};
                                \addplot [asymptote] coordinates {(-7,0.05) (7,0.05)};
                                \addplot [primarycurve, domain=-7:1.857] {1/(x-2)};
                                \addplot [primarycurve, domain=2.143:7] {1/(x-2)};
                                \addplot [soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(-6,-0.125) (-4,-0.167) (-2,-0.25) (0,-0.5) (1,-1) (1.5,-2) (2.5,2) (3,1) (4,0.5) (6,0.25)};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                </sidebyside>

                <p>Note that in <xref ref="figure-rational-function-intro-full-graph">Figure</xref>, the line <m>y=0</m> was also drawn as a dashed line. This is because the values of <m>y=f(x)</m> will be closer and closer to zero as the inputs become more and more positive (or negative).</p>

                <p>We know that the domain of this function is <m>(-\infty,2)\cup(2,\infty)</m> as the function is undefined at <m>2</m>. We can determine this algebraically, and it is also determined by the graph.</p>

                <p>We can see from the graph that the range of the function is <m>(-\infty,0)\cup(0,\infty)</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <remark><p>The line <m>x=2</m> in <xref ref="example-introduction-to-rational-functions">Example</xref> is referred to as a <term>vertical asymptote</term>. The line <m>y=-0</m> is referred to as a <term>horizontal asymptote</term>. We'll use this vocabulary, but the classification of vertical asymptotes is outside the scope of this book.</p></remark>

